namespace
    named namespace
        namespace is a declarative region that provides a scope for 
            > functions
            > classes
            > variables
            > constants
            > templates
        it prevents name collision and helps organize large codebases

        example
            ```
            namespace MyNamespace {
                int value = 1;
                std::cout << value;
            }

            // use it with scope operator
            std::cout << MyNamespace::value;
            ```

    nested namespace
        you can have nested namespaces
        example
            ```
            namespace A {
                namespace B {
                    namespace C {
                    }
                }
            }
            ```

    anonymous namespace
        you can have anonymous namespaces,
        an anonymous namespace make it so that everything inside is only visible to that .cpp file
        so can think of it like file-private-scope

        example
            ```
            namespace {
                int x = 1;
            }
            std::cout << x;
            
            // but cannot use this in another file
            ```

        thus, 
            when two files having the same function names are compiled, it gives linker error
            but if they were in anonymous namespace, no problem since they are visible only within
            their files

template
    often times you can ommit the `<types...>` and the compiler can deduce it
    function
        basic syntax
            ```
            // Declare
            template<Typename T>
            T Add(T a, T b) {
                return a + b;
            }

            // Initialize
            Add<int>(1, 2);
            ```

        multiple parameters
            ```
            // Declare
            template<typename T, typename U>
            auto Add(T a, U b) {
                return a + b;
            }
            
            // Initialize
            Add<int, double>(1, 2.3);
            ```

        class 
