smart pointers
  wrappers around pointers to avoid manual memory management
  if we do manual memory management, errors can lead to
    > memory leaks
    > double frees
    > use after free
    > dangling pointers
      
  
  `#include <memory>` header
  
  ```normal example
  Board* b = new Board;
  delete b;
  ```
  ```with smart pointer
  std::unique_ptr<Board> b = std::make_unique<Board>();
  ```

  smart pointers use RAII (Resource Aquistion Is Initialization)
    basically memory is freed when object goes out of scope
    this is what stack objects do by default

  3 main types of smart pointers
    unique_ptr   ->  single owner
    shared_ptr   ->  multiple owners
    weak_ptr     ->  non owning observer

  unique_ptr
    exclusive ownership

    only one pointer owns the object
    ```std::unique_ptr<Board> b = std::make_unique<Board>();```
    use like a normal pointer
    when out of scope, it gets deleted automatically
    
    ```
      {
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b = std::make_unique<Board>();
      } // deleted
    ```

    cannot copy 
      ```
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b1 = std::make_unique<Board>();
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b2 = b1; // NOT POSSIBLE
      ```

    can move
      ```
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b1 = std::make_unique<Board>();
        std::unique_ptr<Board> b2 = std::move(b1); 
        // b2 now owns the object
        // b1 becomes null
      ```
  shared pointer
    multiple pointers own the same object
    object is deleted when total references become 0

    ```
    {
      std::shared_ptr<Board> b1 = std::make_shared<Board>();
      {
        std::shared_ptr<Board> b2 = b1;
      } // b2 is destroyed, count down to 1
    } // count is 0, object is destroyed

  problem with shared pointers
    suppose we have two shared pointers A and B
    and we set their property so that
      A->b = B  
      B->a = A
    now, they both depend on each other, so they will not be freed when they go out of scope
    because the count doesn't go to 0

    for this there exists weak_ptr
  
  weak_ptr
    doesn't own objects
    
    `weak_ptr<A> a = sharedPtr;` 
    doesnt increase the count

    you cannot directly access the weak pointer since the shared pointer might have been destroyed
    so you have to lock it

    ```
    // wp -> weak pointer
    wp->a; // NOT POSSIBLE

    if (shared_ptr<TypeHere> sp = wp.lock()) {
      std::cout << sp->a;
    }
    ```
    lock()
      returns a shared pointer, if the object is alive
      nullptr if destroyed

    checking expiration
      `wp.expired() // false or true, prefer lock()`

constexpr
  allows you to move computation from runtime to compile time, if the values are known at compile time

  constexpr variables
    `constexpr int x = 1;`
    compiler guarantees value known at compile time 
    stored in read only memory
    can be used in constexpr expressions

  example
    ```
      constexpr int SIZE = 64;
      int board[SIZE]; // compile time, because SIZE is constexpr
    ```

  constexpr functions 
    functions that CAN run at compile time (i.e runtime or compile time based on context)
    ```
        constexpr int square(int x) {
          return x * x;
        }
      constexpr int y = square(5); // compile time
    ```

    this function can also be run time
    ```
      int n;
      std::cin >> n;
      
      int y = square(n); // run time
    ```

    there are many rules for a constexpr function to be compile time evaluable
    some are
      > return literal types
      > simple statements
      > no dynamic allocation
      > no i/o
      > no virtual calls (runtime polymorphism)
      > modern cpp allows loops

  difference between constexpr and const variables
    const -> cannot change value and may or may not be known at compile time
    constexpr -> cannot change value and has to be known at compile time

  constexpr objects
    you can create compile time objects
    ex
      ``` 
        struct Point {
          int x, y;

          constexpr Point(int a, int b) : x(a), y(b) {}
        };
        
        constexpr Point p(3, 2); // compile time
      ```

    constexpr methods

    ```
      struct Square {
        int side;

        constexpr int area() const { // const objects can only all const methods
          return side * side;
        }
      };

      constexpr Square s{5};
      constexpr int a = s.area();
    ```
  
  constexpr if
    lets start with the problem
    suppose we write a template 

    ```
      template<typename T>
      void print(T x) {
        if (std::is_pointer_v<T>) {
          std::cout << *x;
        }
        else {
          std::cout << x;
        }
      }
    ```
    and suppose we call `int a = 5; print(a);`

    it will fail to compile
    because
      templates are compiled at compile time, not run time
      so the compiler sees both branches and sees `*x` which isn't valid for an int, thus compile error

    that is because, the `if` is a runtime condition, whereas the compiler must ensure all code is 
    valid at compile time, thus both branches must compile with normal `if`

    `if constexpr`
      ```
        template<typename T>
        void print(T x) {
          if constexpr (std::is_pointer_v<T>) {
            std::cout << *x;
          }
          else {
            std::cout << x;
          }
        }
      ```
    now it will will work and not fail at compile time 
    because
    the `if constexpr` is evaluated at compile time, i.e the compiler chooses a branch before compiling 
    the whole function and discards the other branch

    normal if -> compile both branches -> runtime decides which to run
    if constexpr -> evaluate condition at compile time -> compile only chosen branch -> other branch deleted

    other way would be to do template for both
      ```
        template<typename T>
        void print(T x) { ... }
        
        template<typename T>
        void print(T* x) { ... }
      ```
      the compiler will chose the correct one at compile time
  

consteval
  MUST be run at compile time, cannot be run at runtime
    ```
      consteval int square(int x) {
        return x * x;
      }

      constexpr int a = square(5);
    ```
  cannot do
    ```
      int n;
      std::cin >> n;
      int a = square(n); // NOT POSSIBLE
    ```
          
const objects and const methods
  const object
    `const Square x{5};`
    this object cannot be modified after creation
      > cannot change its data members
      > cannot call functions that might change it

  const method
    `int area() const { ... }`
    the method promises not to modify the object  
      > can read members 
      > cannot edit members

  const objects can only call const methods

  internally 
    a member function is just a normal function with an extra parameter 
    int area() {}       -> int area(Square* this)
    int area() const {} -> int area( const Square* this)

initialization
  is different from assignment
  ```
    int x = 5; // init
    x = 10;    // assignemnt
  ```
  initialization happens when object is created

  default initialization
  when you declare a variable without giving a value
    primitive types
      ```
        int x;
      ```
      these are unintialized, they contain garbage values

    arrays
      ```
        int arr[10];
      ```
      these are uninitialized too, because the contained element is int, which is defaulted to garbage
      if it were strings, it would be empty strings

    ptrs 
      ```
        int* ptr; 
      ```
      garbage address
    
    class types
      here the default constructor are run
      ```
        std::string s;
        std::vector<int> v;
      ```
      s -> ""
      v -> empty vector
      
      for custom classes/structs the members are also default initialized according to their types
   
  value initialization
      value initialization
        step 1. -> zero initialize memory
        step 2. -> calls default constructor, (NOTE: in custom classes/ structs if you only have 
                                                parameterized constructor, value initialization will fail
                                                you will have to do list initilaization, or direct
                                                intialization)

    primitives
      ```
        int x{};
        double y{}'
      ```
      result -> x is 0, y is 0.0

    arrays 
      ```
        int arr[10]{};
      ```
      filled with 0s

    ptrs
      ```
        int* ptr{}
      ```
      nullptr
    
    class types
      same as before, the default constructor is called
      `std::string s{}` same as `std::string s`

    for custom classes/ structs the value initialization for each member is called

  zero initialization
    low-level step where memory is set to 0

    happens automatically for
      > global variables
      > static variables

  direct initialization
    calls constructor with parameters
    ```
      int x(5); // you can also do int x(5.33) and it will auto narrow
                  // to avoid that, use list initialzation which doesn't allow for narrowing and causes error
      std::string s("hello");
    ```

  copy initialization
    ```
      int x = 5;
    ```
    afaik compilers optimize this 

    its actually a little confusing 
    ```
      struct A {
        A(int x) { ... }
      };

      int x = 3;
      A a = x; // WORKS, the compiler calls the A(int) constructor
               // think of it this way, the compiler implicitly converts 3 to type `A`
               //   it create a A object from 3 and then copy constructs 
               //   it to the left side variables

      double y = 3.0;
      A a = y; // WORKS, the compiler calls the A(int) constructor and implictly converts the double
               // think of it this way, the compiler implicitly converts 3.0 to type `A`
               //   the compiler implicitly converts 3.0 to 3 and then creates 
               //   an A object from 3 and then copy constructs it to the left side variable
    ```
    i.e copy initilazation allows for implicit conversion
    because of this, it DOES NOT work when we have explicit constructors

    ex
      ```
        struct A {
            explicit A(int x) { ... } 
        };

        A a = 3; // DOESNT WORK, because the complier cannot implictly convert 3 to type `A`
                 // have to use direct, list initilaiation
                 // although direct intialazation also doesn't enforce narrowing
                 // use list for that

  list initialization
    prefer this, at this point I dont know why there are so many types of initialization
    when multiple constructors, it preferes the one if exists, initializer_list<>
    ```
      int x{5};
      double d{3.2};

      int arr[5]{1,2,3};

      struct M { int from; int to; };
      M m{1, 2};

      std::vector<int> v{1, 2, 3}; // uses vector's intializer_list<> constructor
          // can be confused here
          // std::vector<int> v(3); means 3 elements initialized to 0
          //    std::vector<int> v(3, 4); means 3 elements intialization to 4
          // std::vector<int> v{3}; means 1 element intialized to 3
          //    std::vector<int> v{3, 4}; means {3, 4}
    ```
    here compiler blocks narrowing, whereas in copy and direct the compiler used to allow
    so cannot do `int x{1.2}`

